# Plan: `ze config completion` CLI command

## Context

The `ze config edit` completion system (YANG-driven, in `completer.go`) has bugs that are hard to diagnose because completion can only be tested through:
1. Unit tests against the `Completer` type directly (no config context)
2. `.et` functional tests driving the full TUI headlessly (heavyweight, slow)

Neither approach supports quick command-line probing of "what completions does this input produce at this path?" — the kind of thing needed to triage bugs and write regression tests.

## Approach: `ze config completion` subcommand

A new non-interactive CLI command that loads a config file + YANG schema, queries the `Completer`, and prints results to stdout.

### Interface

```
ze config completion [options] <config-file> [input-text]

Options:
  --context <path>   Dot-separated context path (e.g., "bgp.peer.1.1.1.1")
  --json             Output as JSON (default: text table)
  --ghost            Show ghost text instead of completions

Examples:
  ze config completion config.conf "set "
  ze config completion config.conf "set " --context bgp
  ze config completion config.conf "set local" --context bgp
  ze config completion config.conf "edit " --context bgp
  ze config completion config.conf --json "set p" --context bgp.peer.1.1.1.1
  ze config completion config.conf --ghost "set router" --context bgp
```

### Text output format (default)

```
TYPE        TEXT            DESCRIPTION
keyword     local-as        Local AS number (required)
keyword     router-id       Router identifier
keyword     peer            BGP peers
```

For ghost: prints just the ghost text string (or empty line).

### JSON output format

```json
[{"text":"local-as","description":"Local AS number (required)","type":"keyword"},...]
```

For ghost: `{"ghost":"<text>"}`.

